# `@mastra/core` deliberately bundles `@ai-sdk/ui-utils@1.2.11` under an
# alias (`@ai-sdk/ui-utils-v5`) so it can support both v5 and v6 of the
# Vercel AI SDK in the same install. That bundled v5 copy declares
# `peer zod@^3`, while our root project uses `zod@4` (required by
# `ai@6`). The two zods coexist at different nesting depths in
# node_modules and the runtime is unaffected — 38/38 tests pass — but
# npm 7+ floods stdout with peer-mismatch warnings on every install.
#
# `legacy-peer-deps=true` restores the npm 6 behavior of installing
# peers only when explicitly asked and not enforcing peer-version
# matches at install time. This is the standard workaround for
# AI/ML dep trees with framework-level peer conflicts.
#
# Trade-off: if a NEW dependency we add later has a legitimately
# broken peer dep, npm won't surface it here. Periodically re-evaluate
# by running `npm install --no-legacy-peer-deps` and checking the
# warnings have a known cause.
legacy-peer-deps=true
